 not develop. At issue is how death reveals the emptiness of all identity, which demands that life and death no longer be conceived as purely oppositional. If mortal death can appear at the very origin of life, then the fullness or presence of life is at each instant threatened by the possibility of its negation. Through a reading of the works of such major artistic and intellectual figures as Kurosawa Akira, Tsai Ming-liang, Lu Xun, and Takeuchi Yoshimi, The Coming Death argues for a fundamental rethinking of mortality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDeath in literature. 0aDeath in motion pictures. 0aEast Asian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aEast Asian literature-History and criticism. 0aMortality in literature. 0aMortality in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszEast AsiaxHistory. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Japanese Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aPsychology : Death and Dying. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848730440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438487304423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438487304/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles